body:
 Just confirming it's not a bug and that the only the given directory is inspected. 

Having said that, there is room for similar assertions with a recursive traversal of all subdirectories.
Possible syntax:
```java
//  - 1
boolean recursively = true;
assertThat(outputDirectory).isDirectoryContaining("glob:**.java", recursively);
// - 2 
assertThat(outputDirectory).isDirectoryOrSubdirectoriesContaining("glob:**.java");
// - 3 
assertThat(outputDirectory).isDirectoryRecursivelyContaining("glob:**.java");
```
@LorenzoBettini WDYT? any better naming?

@joel-costigliola 
Hello,

If not implemented yet, I can work on it.

In `org.assertj.core.internal.Files`,  is there any reason to not use the Java 7 Path API to perform the processings ? 

In assert methods I will add, for example  `assertIsDirectoryRecursivelyContaining()`,  in order to prevent iterate files more than required and to keep the code simple, I would like to favor `Files.walk(actual.toPath())` to some recursive call to `File.listFiles(FileFilter)` +  such as : 

```
private void assertIsDirectoryRecursivelyContaining(AssertionInfo info, File actual, Predicate<File> filter, String filterPresentation) {
      //...
      boolean isAnyMatch = java.nio.file.Files.walk(actual.toPath())
                                     .map(Path::toFile)
                                     .anyMatch(filter);
      //...
}


```

Agreed. Let's go.

Edit : 
Concretely, the test part will be complicated because of FilesBaseTest.mockDirectory() that is strongly coupled with the  methods invoked by the implementation but that overall reimplementsthe JDK `Files.listFiles() `. It is rather annoying since the mock record serves finally as an implementation of the core logic of the SUT : 

```  protected File mockDirectory(List<File> directoryFiles, String... names) {
    //...
    // re-implement listFiles(FileFilter) ... :(
    Map<String, File> filesByName = directoryFiles.stream().collect(LinkedHashMap::new, // for consistent ordering
                                                                    (map, item) -> map.put(item.getName(), item),
                                                                    Map::putAll);
    given(file.listFiles(any(FileFilter.class))).will(invocation -> {
      FileFilter filter = invocation.getArgument(0);
      return filesByName.keySet().stream()
                        .map(name -> filesByName.get(name))
                        .filter(fileWithName -> filter.accept(fileWithName))
                        .toArray(File[]::new);
    });
    return file;
  }
```
I understand that that thing is not necessarily desirable and that it was probably done to mitigate the FS portability problem.
Right now, I prefer stopping and getting your mind too.
I suppose we have mainly two possibilities : 
- Create another `mockDirectory()` method with a recursively search written at the hand. Easy but that also means creating more technical debt.
- Think about a alternative.

Let me know your opinion
